As I stated in the previous question, I love the 100% cotton merchantile jacket, regular and 3/4 sleeve. I have purchased 30-40 of them. I was extremely disappointed in the newer version that is a synthetic blend. It looks pretty but the sizes were way off and the fabric “pills” almost immediately after wearing. The availability has been spotty to nonexistent for the 100% cotton for several years. I’ve purchased these from XCVI directly, and from Target(wearables). The 100% cotton is amazing! 
The blend that I purchased from QVC did not fit, and the fabric was inferior. I also had issues with returning the item. So now I’m stuck with one that doesn’t fit.

I wish you had more of the 100% cotton ones available. I did purchase quite a few in the oakmoss, 6 i think and just recently in black 3 and oil washed graphite 2. that they came in the newer colors. They only had one medium black 3/4 available and no Large black 3/4 ones when I received an email saying they were back in stock. I love your 100% cotton French terry and have a few other styles, one that buttoned down the front and had a longer back, kind of like a riding jacket ran very small. The xlarge  didn’t even fit. I am consistently a medium in the 100% cotton French terry.

Sizing is not consistent, and this is especially problematic for online sales.  Better photos clearly showing the cut and drape, plus measurements of pit-to-pit, bottom edge diameter, sleeve length, are needed when sizing is not consistent.  For returns, some customers don’t have equipment to print return mailing labels.  For ease of shopping, your website needs updating to include a search feature sensitive to item type, item name, item color.  Back up feature to previous screen needs a lot of improvement. More information regarding characteristics of fabric would be helpful.  Your fabric colors are a huge selling point, but there needs to be more information describing the colors beyond the ambiguous names you assign.  And a feature that provides help in coordinating pieces in the beautiful pallets you offer would be much appreciated (maybe an expansion of the “get the look” feature.

On the positive your clothes are super comfortable, great quality and unique colors- unlike any other company I purchase clothing from! Huge fan!

column13: I'm 5'1" and I can only wear your Jetter Crop style (or similar length) because they hit me at the ankle - which is perfect for warm weather wear (with sandals or sneakers). The other pants styles you carry are either not flattering (I will not be wearing actual crop styles anytime soon because they hit me just below the knee) or they are so long as to be ridiculous. I have no interest in buying causal clothing that I have to have altered either. And the problem with a lot of your tops is that they are often billowy, flowy, lots of fabric, too long, etc. They are not suitable for someone my size -- they are overwhelming. And I'm not a size 0 either -- I can fluctuate anywhere between a size 8P, 10P, 12P or even a 14P. But it doesn't matter which size I might be at a given time in my life, I cannot handle a large volume of fabric that engulfs my frame. While I do enjoy wearing the few pants styles I find flattering, I seldom find any other styles in your store that are flattering. Also - please note that clingy/jersey fabrics are not flattering on many "mature" bodies. Such fabrics for tops enhance every figure flaw imaginable.
column14: In general, you do not have styles that flatter short women -- especially if they are on the "mature" side. You either carry styles that look great on very slim bodies or on very tall bodies. But if an older woman is short (say 5'1") - forget it. A short woman cannot easily pull off billowing/flowing styles. And pants or dresses that require a tall woman to carry off (without alterations) are of no use to a short person. Please do a better job of sizing products for short women.

column13:
Sizing is inconsistent. Often different colours of the same clothing item are quite a bit larger or smaller. 

The colours of clothing on the website are also very inconsistent. It’s hard to tell what colour a piece of clothing will actually be when photos of different items in that colour are completely different. For example, pants and leggings in Sumac Pigment look burgundy in some photos and rust or even burnt orange in others.

Sometimes the descriptions of items are highly inaccurate. For example, I recently bought a pair of Grassroots Cord Leggings. I have two pairs of Grassroots leggings in the regular cotton fabric and they fit perfectly -  snug and fitted like you would expect from a legging.  The cord version were a completely different fit: huge in the waste and a full four inches bigger around in the legs, calves and ankles. The were like a baggy pant instead of a legging. When I called customer service, assuming that the leggings were labelled as a small but were actually a large, I was told that that is the way the cord version are sized, and that the baggy cord pant I received is intended to be that way. 

If this is the case, why would you call the cord version a legging? Why not call it the Grassroots cord pant?

I live in Canada and pay a lot in shipping fees and duty and exchange rates (as our dollar is worth about 30% less than the US dollar). It would be too expensive to ship things back when I need to return something, so having consistent sizing, accurate descriptions, and being able to know what a colour really looks like is important. 

I have purchased a lot of XCVi clothing in the past few years, but I’m not sure I will continue after the cord leggings and a few other tops I’ve purchased that turned out to be a completely different colour or size than expected.

Pricey

1) Many of your items are not long enough for me as a 5’10” somewhat full figured woman. 
2) I cannot wear synthetics (polyester, rayon, etc.) so that limits choices. A little spandex is ok.
3) I live in Northern Ohio...currently 20 degrees. It will not be warm enough for most of your clothes until probably late April at best. 
4) It’s hard to judge colors by the creative names. The added descriptors, when used, do help.
column14: One of my favorite XCVI tops to wear in the spring is a coral color zip-up jacket with ruching in the front, a neckline that hugs the neck and a somewhat asymmetrical hem. It is starting to look a bit worn out and I’d like to replace it at some point...not sure you have anything quite like it.

column13: Your plus sizes are so very limited in color & style. I would buy so much more if you offered more options for bottoms in plus sizes. It’s really disappointing to get an email about a new style or color only to find that you don’t offer it in my size.
